HEADWORD: grotesquery
<hw>gro*tesqu"er*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>grotesquerie</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[From <er>Grotesque</er>.]</ety>
<def>Grotesque action, speech, or manners; grotesque doings; ludicrous
or incongruous unnaturalness or distortion.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The sustained
<xex>grotesquery</xex> of Feather-top.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>K. L.
Bates.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> grotesqueness.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><q>Vileness, on the other hand, becomes <qex>grotesquerie</qex>,
wonderfully converted into a subject of laughter.</q> <rj><qau>George
Gissing.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>grotto</ent>⟦br⟧
